WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.878
♪

00:02.878 --> 00:05.255
- Who wants to go to Broadway?

00:05.255 --> 00:08.175
[all cheering]
I welcome you all...

00:08.175 --> 00:09.635
to the world...

00:09.635 --> 00:11.595
of Death Rattle!

00:11.595 --> 00:13.639
- Well, my friends are
just beside themselves

00:13.639 --> 00:15.599
that I'm gonna get to work with the CoBro!

00:15.599 --> 00:17.309
- I'm just the friendly zoologist

00:17.309 --> 00:20.479
who morphs into a 20-foot cobra

00:20.479 --> 00:22.856
and helps the cops save the day.

00:22.856 --> 00:25.150
Hey, you.
- I loved you in Girl Cop.

00:25.150 --> 00:26.818
♪

00:26.818 --> 00:28.320
[blows]
Oh!

00:29.696 --> 00:32.031
OLIVER: Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
Oh, my God. He's dead.

00:32.031 --> 00:34.243
He's dead. Ben's dead.
My leading man is dead!

00:34.243 --> 00:36.537
- At least you had the consideration
to keep the body

00:36.537 --> 00:38.330
out of the building this time.

00:38.330 --> 00:41.041
- My first thought when he went down?

00:41.041 --> 00:42.459
Maybe he was poisoned.

00:42.459 --> 00:46.797
And a podcast about
the poisoning of a big movie star?

00:46.797 --> 00:49.007
That could be huge.

00:49.007 --> 00:50.342
[crowd gasping]

00:50.342 --> 00:52.636
- Mama's back, bitches!

00:52.636 --> 00:55.055
That's right. I'm alive!

00:55.055 --> 00:56.640
- Word is out. Ben is back.

00:56.640 --> 00:58.517
[liquid dripping]

00:58.517 --> 01:00.352
[glass cracking]

01:00.352 --> 01:02.271
[crash]
[Uma screams]

01:06.358 --> 01:08.527
[quiet heart beating]

01:08.527 --> 01:11.947
♪

01:11.947 --> 01:13.198
BEN:
When you're falling...

01:13.198 --> 01:14.700
[muffled whooshing]

01:14.700 --> 01:17.202
...all you can hear is your heartbeat.

01:17.202 --> 01:19.913
It's been beating since
the moment you were born,

01:19.913 --> 01:22.958
and you never paid it any mind.

01:22.958 --> 01:24.793
And now,

01:24.793 --> 01:27.796
the last thought
that pops into your head,

01:28.630 --> 01:30.632
right before you hit the ground,

01:32.509 --> 01:35.220
"I should have listened to it
while I still had the chance.

01:35.220 --> 01:38.307
"Because if I'd listened
to that heartbeat,

01:41.143 --> 01:43.645
maybe none of this would've happened."

01:45.314 --> 01:47.316
[rubber stretching, pops]

01:50.986 --> 01:54.698
I'm sorry.
What did fucking happen in this play?

01:54.698 --> 01:56.700
This woman got choked with a rattle

01:56.700 --> 01:59.328
and thrown off the top
of the Pickwick Lighthouse,

01:59.328 --> 02:02.873
and our audience is supposed to think
a baby is my prime suspect?

02:02.873 --> 02:04.499
- Well, yes and no because the author--

02:04.499 --> 02:07.503
- Well, what is it, Oliver?
Because I don't live in the gray.

02:08.504 --> 02:10.422
CoBro doesn't live in the gray.

02:10.422 --> 02:13.509
Is he a cobra? Yeah.
Is he a bro? Yeah.

02:13.509 --> 02:15.093
That's how you gross two bill.

02:15.093 --> 02:17.387
Not with subtle. Subtle doesn't sell.
[rattling]

02:18.514 --> 02:21.642
- First of all, do you see
this paisley neckcloth?

02:21.642 --> 02:24.144
I have never been accused of being subtle.

02:24.144 --> 02:26.688
And second, Ben, Ben,

02:26.688 --> 02:28.899
rehearsal's a process.

02:28.899 --> 02:31.610
This is our first week with this material.
[Ben sighs]

02:32.778 --> 02:35.822
When the curtain goes up
in three months on opening night,

02:35.822 --> 02:37.324
trust me.

02:37.324 --> 02:38.492
You're gonna kill.

02:38.492 --> 02:39.493
[door slams shut]

02:39.493 --> 02:42.079
KT:
No, he definitely died the second time.

02:42.079 --> 02:43.956
Oh shit, gotta go.

02:43.956 --> 02:47.376
- [grunts] KT. KT. KT! Wait.

02:47.376 --> 02:48.502
Wait!

02:48.502 --> 02:51.588
Okay, wh-why are there people
out there striking our sets?

02:51.588 --> 02:53.423
- Sorry, Oliver. I've got my orders.

02:53.423 --> 02:55.342
- Well, I'm ordering you to stop.

02:55.342 --> 02:56.885
This has to stop!

02:58.387 --> 02:59.888
Thank you.

02:59.888 --> 03:01.515
Now, I'm gonna call my producer

03:01.515 --> 03:04.309
and show you that
we are all on the same page.

03:04.309 --> 03:05.435
[dial tone]

03:05.435 --> 03:06.854
DONNA DEMEO [on phone]:
You've reached Donna Demeo,

03:06.854 --> 03:09.022
CEO and founder of Demeo Productions.
Leave your--

03:09.022 --> 03:12.568
- Okay. Well, I'll try the other producer,
the son.

03:12.568 --> 03:15.404
CLIFF [on phone]: Hi, it's Cliff Demeo.
I am also a professional now--

03:15.404 --> 03:17.281
- Okay, the reception here is dogshit.
[hangs up]

03:17.281 --> 03:20.701
- They're pulling the plug, Oliver.
They just don't wanna say it to your face.

03:20.701 --> 03:24.162
[construction noise]
- Well, then I need to go to them.

03:24.830 --> 03:27.749
And she's going with me! Gimme!
- What? No!

03:27.749 --> 03:30.627
[both struggling, yelling]

03:30.627 --> 03:33.839
- And you can tell
those workers onstage right now

03:33.839 --> 03:36.842
that if anyone lays
another finger on my sets,

03:36.842 --> 03:38.260
I'm gonna wrestle them, too.

03:38.260 --> 03:40.220
♪

03:40.220 --> 03:42.431
And Oliver Putnam never taps out!

03:42.431 --> 03:46.393
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

03:46.393 --> 03:49.396
♪ vocalizing ♪

04:31.605 --> 04:34.900
[distant street noise]

04:34.900 --> 04:37.152
- I don't know, Bruce.
The drug bust is tonight.

04:37.152 --> 04:39.196
What if I'm not back
in time for homecoming?

04:41.323 --> 04:43.742
- Guess you just have to speed.
[keys jingling]

04:44.660 --> 04:47.037
- Your dad's Saab?
If my sergeant finds out,

04:47.037 --> 04:49.665
he'll take my badge
and my learner's permit.

04:49.665 --> 04:52.793
- Save you a dance, Girl Cop.
[truck reverse beeping]

04:52.793 --> 04:55.879
♪ upbeat '80s music playing ♪

04:59.258 --> 05:00.259
[both blow]

05:02.219 --> 05:03.220
[video stops]

05:10.060 --> 05:12.729
♪

05:14.439 --> 05:17.150
CHARLES:
Lester! Security!

05:17.150 --> 05:18.402
OLIVER:
Lester!

05:25.951 --> 05:29.413
[shutter snapping]

05:47.556 --> 05:49.224
- You took those, didn't you?

05:50.976 --> 05:52.269
'Sup?

05:53.145 --> 05:55.689
- God, I had such a crush on you
in middle school.

05:55.689 --> 05:58.567
- Really?
What are you now? Like, a senior?

05:59.234 --> 06:01.528
- No, I-I actually
graduated a few years ago.

06:01.528 --> 06:03.363
I-I'm 29.

06:03.363 --> 06:04.615
- Tight.

06:05.866 --> 06:07.576
So, you're, like,

06:07.576 --> 06:09.203
done with college and working already?

06:09.203 --> 06:11.622
- I didn't finish college.

06:11.622 --> 06:12.956
- Tight.

06:13.832 --> 06:14.833
Tight.

06:15.876 --> 06:17.878
Hey, at least you landed
this sick apartment.

06:18.962 --> 06:20.547
- It's my aunt's,

06:20.547 --> 06:22.883
and I have to be out in a few weeks.

06:22.883 --> 06:24.885
- Oh. Okay.

06:25.552 --> 06:26.803
Okay.

06:27.679 --> 06:30.098
That's, uh--
- The opposite of tight.

06:31.308 --> 06:34.561
[sighs] I'm almost 30, and I have...

06:34.561 --> 06:37.022
nothing figured out.

06:37.022 --> 06:38.524
I should be...

06:39.233 --> 06:41.735
finding a job or a place to live,

06:41.735 --> 06:44.238
and, instead, all I can think about is...

06:46.490 --> 06:48.909
I don't know. I'm just lost.

06:50.536 --> 06:53.205
- You know, I was your age
when I played this part.

06:53.956 --> 06:56.375
- Yeah, I know. You were young and rich.

06:56.375 --> 06:57.876
That makes me feel way better.

06:57.876 --> 07:01.380
- No, I was a 31-year-old man
playing a high school senior.

07:02.339 --> 07:04.842
I was lost. And lonely.

07:04.842 --> 07:06.385
♪

07:06.385 --> 07:09.513
And they hadn't invented Propecia yet,
so I was also terrified.

07:10.681 --> 07:13.809
But, worst of all,
I was jealous of everyone else.

07:14.393 --> 07:17.354
My broke actor friends doing
off-Broadway plays for free?

07:17.354 --> 07:20.399
They had artistic integrity.
All the people I grew up with?

07:20.399 --> 07:24.194
They had real jobs,
kids they loved, families.

07:24.194 --> 07:27.155
But, it didn't do me any good
to compare myself to 'em.

07:28.407 --> 07:31.660
The people who figure their shit out
right away are boring.

07:31.660 --> 07:33.620
The late bloomers?

07:33.620 --> 07:35.789
People like us?

07:35.789 --> 07:37.374
We make the world go round.

07:38.166 --> 07:40.169
You can afford to take your time, Mabel.

07:41.461 --> 07:44.173
What you can't afford to do is waste it.

07:44.173 --> 07:47.092
♪

07:47.092 --> 07:48.135
- Thanks.

07:49.720 --> 07:53.473
This is nice. I haven't spoken
to a dead person since Tim Kono.

07:53.473 --> 07:54.516
- I'm dead?

07:55.893 --> 07:57.477
I'm kiddin'. I knew.

07:58.896 --> 08:00.939
You'll figure it out.

08:02.024 --> 08:04.067
- My shit or who killed you?

08:05.152 --> 08:06.695
- I'm bettin' on both.

08:08.488 --> 08:10.365
- Is it weird if we do the handshake?

08:17.331 --> 08:18.332
[blows]

08:27.257 --> 08:28.300
CHARLES:
Mm.

08:31.261 --> 08:34.139
[door opens, shuts]
OLIVER: Charles? Are you home?

08:34.139 --> 08:36.600
I'm in desperate need of your help.

08:36.600 --> 08:39.603
I have these scarves. Do you think
they're too much for a funeral?

08:39.603 --> 08:42.940
O-Or do you have something I can borrow
from your incredibly bland wardrobe?

08:42.940 --> 08:44.191
- Huh?

08:44.191 --> 08:45.943
- I didn't realize you were
going to the funeral.

08:45.943 --> 08:47.486
- Why would I not go to the funeral?

08:47.486 --> 08:49.530
- Well, I mean, it's more of a...

08:49.530 --> 08:51.949
fancy who's who kind of thing.

08:51.949 --> 08:54.034
A-And, you know, you and Ben--

08:54.034 --> 08:57.496
- Had a complicated but ultimately
copacetic working relationship.

08:57.496 --> 08:59.248
- [growls] I hope you gave the police

08:59.248 --> 09:00.916
a better performance
than whatever that was.

09:00.916 --> 09:02.835
- I gave them an honest statement,

09:02.835 --> 09:05.337
not to mention a complete list
of alibi witnesses,

09:05.337 --> 09:07.464
and a doctor's note saying

09:07.464 --> 09:08.841
I'm too weak to kill!

09:08.841 --> 09:10.259
Ow.
- Jesus.

09:10.259 --> 09:14.012
I do not have time to plumb
the depths of your conscience.

09:14.012 --> 09:15.806
Donna and Cliff are dodging my calls.

09:15.806 --> 09:17.558
I have to convince them
not to kill my show.

09:17.558 --> 09:20.060
- Oh, so now you're the victim here
and not the man in the box.

09:20.060 --> 09:23.105
- All I need is five minutes.
Give me five minutes in a room,

09:23.105 --> 09:26.400
and I can convince anyone of anything.
- That is not true.

09:26.400 --> 09:28.360
- I convinced you to get Paramount Plus.

09:28.360 --> 09:30.863
- No, I wanted that!
- Did you?

09:31.613 --> 09:32.614
[sighs]

09:32.614 --> 09:33.699
Hey!
- Hey!

09:33.699 --> 09:35.075
- Can I come with you to the funeral?

09:35.075 --> 09:37.995
- Yeah.
- Oh, please, God, yes! W-We need you!

09:37.995 --> 09:41.540
You're the glue. You're the Mabel
in the Charles-Oliver sandwich.

09:41.540 --> 09:43.750
- Without you, we're just two pieces
of stale white bread.

09:43.750 --> 09:45.252
- Exactly. Come on!

09:46.545 --> 09:48.046
- Hey, you didn't really know, Ben.

09:48.046 --> 09:50.340
Are you still crushing on him
or something?

09:50.340 --> 09:52.759
- No.
- Then, you're sleuthing?

09:52.759 --> 09:54.011
- Obviously.

09:54.011 --> 09:57.055
♪

09:57.055 --> 10:00.058
[quiet chatter]

10:10.736 --> 10:13.739
♪ muffled choir singing ♪

10:13.739 --> 10:15.157
- Yes, Oliver Putnam?

10:15.157 --> 10:17.159
- Yes, welcome.

10:20.370 --> 10:22.789
♪ choir continues ♪

10:22.789 --> 10:24.208
[Oliver snorts]

10:24.208 --> 10:26.585
♪

10:26.585 --> 10:29.171
CHARLES:
Is that Ben's funeral on the TV?

10:29.171 --> 10:30.589
USHER:
Closed circuit from upstairs.

10:30.589 --> 10:32.549
- No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

10:32.549 --> 10:34.092
I-I was sent here by mistake.

10:34.092 --> 10:36.220
I should be upstairs in the action

10:36.220 --> 10:39.014
with beloved friends, family,
and showbiz power players,

10:39.014 --> 10:41.600
not... with this pack of nobodies.

10:41.600 --> 10:43.101
- Hi, Charles-Haden Savage.

10:43.101 --> 10:45.812
- No, you're in the right place.
This is overflow three.

10:46.230 --> 10:48.106
- I'm sorry, overflow three?

10:48.106 --> 10:49.691
- Why does that sound like
a plumbing emergency?

10:49.691 --> 10:51.985
Like a very low priority
plumbing emergency.

10:52.694 --> 10:53.820
- And your name?

10:53.820 --> 10:56.615
- Mabel Mora.
I-I wouldn't be on the list.

10:56.615 --> 10:58.408
- Ah, then overflow three.

10:58.408 --> 11:00.702
- Hold on.
Complete strangers get overflow three?

11:01.328 --> 11:02.955
- Why don't we take a seat, shall we?

11:02.955 --> 11:04.915
[quiet chatter]
[Oliver sighs]

11:04.915 --> 11:06.416
Hurry.

11:07.084 --> 11:09.586
I'm gonna look around. Behave yourselves.

11:09.586 --> 11:13.006
♪ choir continues ♪

11:13.006 --> 11:15.509
- Cliff and Donna have to be
up there somewhere.

11:16.134 --> 11:19.388
I bet they have prime seats up there
on the main part of the cathedral.

11:19.388 --> 11:21.515
You know, the whatchamacallit.

11:21.515 --> 11:24.142
- The transept.
- No, no, no. That's the cross-section.

11:24.142 --> 11:27.604
I'm talking about the main part.
- The narthex, the antechamber.

11:28.230 --> 11:30.858
- Who are you,
the Hunchback of Notre Dame?

11:30.858 --> 11:34.611
I didn't I know was attending a funeral
with famous church architect, Sir...

11:34.611 --> 11:36.488
- Sir Christopher Wren.
- Okay, okay, okay.

11:36.488 --> 11:39.241
Congrats on winning Jeopardy!
- Well, for God's sake, do a crossword.

11:39.241 --> 11:41.994
- [sighs] I gotta get up there!

11:41.994 --> 11:43.495
- Shh!
- Sorry.

11:43.495 --> 11:46.498
♪ choir continues ♪

11:47.875 --> 11:50.586
Okay, okay.
This is gonna be tricky

11:51.420 --> 11:54.298
but I need you to draw
attention to yourself.

11:54.298 --> 11:56.383
Now, you won't be able
to do it with charisma,

11:56.383 --> 11:58.927
but maybe if you make
a loud noise to distract the usher.

11:58.927 --> 12:00.179
- I'm not doing that.

12:02.389 --> 12:05.434
- Something's rotten
in the state of Denmark.

12:06.268 --> 12:07.311
- Hamlet?

12:08.145 --> 12:09.563
- No, Gregg.

12:10.772 --> 12:12.274
Oh yeah, Hamlet.

12:12.274 --> 12:14.776
- I'm Mabel.
- Mabel Mora.

12:14.776 --> 12:17.446
Your reputation precedes you.
I did security for Ben.

12:17.446 --> 12:19.448
- Oh. Security.

12:20.199 --> 12:21.700
I mean, then you must know all about--

12:21.700 --> 12:25.162
- Threats, crazy fans, restraining orders.
Yeah. [laughs]

12:25.162 --> 12:27.456
I got a whole filing cabinet
of that stuff.

12:27.456 --> 12:29.082
When you work security,

12:29.082 --> 12:31.627
you learn to look at a crowd
and pick out the troublemakers.

12:31.627 --> 12:33.504
Like the ones from his play.

12:33.504 --> 12:37.424
Kimber. Harmless ingenue,
or a woman scorned?

12:37.424 --> 12:41.303
And Ty. Strapping heartthrob,
or over-ambitious hothead?

12:42.137 --> 12:43.722
And Bobo? [laughs]

12:44.473 --> 12:47.309
That one writes itself.
[crunching]

12:47.309 --> 12:49.603
- Sounds like you're investigating.

12:49.603 --> 12:51.063
- Aren't you?

12:51.063 --> 12:53.148
You should come look at my files.

12:53.148 --> 12:54.775
Bring the old guys if you want.

12:54.775 --> 12:56.193
- Have you shown them to the cops?

12:56.777 --> 12:58.445
- I don't trust the cops.

13:00.697 --> 13:04.660
PRIEST [on TV]: And now, a remembrance
from Ben's good friend, Michael Musaleks.

13:06.119 --> 13:10.082
- When I think of Ben,
I think of resiliency.

13:11.041 --> 13:15.003
He was an actor, after all.
Actors need to be resilient.

13:15.003 --> 13:18.966
Ben was fired from his first TV show.

13:19.550 --> 13:22.052
Yep. Eight years old.

13:23.136 --> 13:25.681
[loud ringtone of Charles singing]:
♪ It's a angel in flip-flops ♪

13:25.681 --> 13:28.016
- Silence all phones, please.

13:28.016 --> 13:30.394
- ♪ Angel in flip-flops, short-- ♪

13:34.231 --> 13:37.526
- [exhales] Hey. I think I got a lead.
Are you gonna be okay by yourself?

13:37.526 --> 13:39.570
- No!
- [sighs] Go. Go.

13:40.654 --> 13:43.282
PRIEST [on TV]: Please join me
in welcoming Mr. Harry Styles.

13:43.282 --> 13:46.577
[applause, cheering]

13:46.577 --> 13:49.621
♪

13:51.290 --> 13:53.041
[door unlocking]

13:53.041 --> 13:55.169
- Ta-da.
[keys jingling]

13:55.169 --> 13:56.420
[soft laugh]

13:58.046 --> 14:00.674
Um, do you mind taking your shoes off?

14:00.674 --> 14:02.509
- Oh, I have, uh, plantar fasciitis.

14:02.509 --> 14:05.888
If I step on a grain of sand,
it feels like a shard of glass.

14:07.222 --> 14:09.183
Oh, okay. Well...

14:10.350 --> 14:12.561
- Whoa.
- I know, I know.

14:12.561 --> 14:14.479
It's-- [laughs]
- Amazing!

14:14.479 --> 14:15.856
- Wait, are you a fan?
- Uh-huh.

14:15.856 --> 14:17.232
- Oh. Well, then you're gonna love this.

14:17.232 --> 14:20.235
♪

14:21.612 --> 14:23.405
- Holy shit!

14:31.580 --> 14:32.831
[gasps] Oh, my gosh.

14:32.831 --> 14:35.334
Are these the car keys from Girl Cop?

14:35.334 --> 14:36.460
- Ben gave them to me.

14:36.460 --> 14:38.754
That's the helmet from Chinook Rising.
[sniffs]

14:38.754 --> 14:41.924
Those are the sneakers from
Labrador Receiver. [snarls]

14:42.549 --> 14:44.510
- What are these?
- Those are Ben's pants.

14:44.510 --> 14:46.261
- Wow! From...

14:46.261 --> 14:47.638
- Old Navy.

14:48.847 --> 14:52.309
- Oh. So, uh, you did security for Ben.

14:52.309 --> 14:53.852
How come I never noticed you before?

14:53.852 --> 14:56.146
- I don't know.
I'm good at my job? [laughs]

14:56.146 --> 14:57.648
[awkward laughter]

14:57.648 --> 14:59.441
- Uh, Gregg, about those files
you were gonna show us.

14:59.441 --> 15:01.860
- Oh, right. Stay here.
[bell jingling]

15:01.860 --> 15:03.278
Oop!
[squeak]

15:03.278 --> 15:05.739
Ben wants to say hi.

15:05.739 --> 15:07.824
- Oh. That's Ben! He's cute.

15:07.824 --> 15:10.285
- She.
- Oh.

15:12.454 --> 15:14.456
[Ben snarls]
- [whispers] Okay, we have to go.

15:14.456 --> 15:16.959
- [whispers] No. You can go.
I wanna see what he has to show us.

15:16.959 --> 15:19.378
- What, a-an ant farm
with a thousand little Bens?

15:19.378 --> 15:21.213
The man has an unhealthy vibe.

15:21.213 --> 15:24.132
- He's a fan.
- H-He's a psycho.

15:24.132 --> 15:26.343
- Oh, he's harmless. I mean...
[Ben barking]

15:26.343 --> 15:28.387
Look, they're friends. They're--

15:28.387 --> 15:32.057
♪

15:32.057 --> 15:34.977
Oh shit, that's Photoshopped.

15:34.977 --> 15:37.980
- This is why I should
never take off my shoes.

15:38.689 --> 15:41.900
MABEL: What are you-- [muffled]
[body thuds]

15:42.651 --> 15:44.653
- Mabel! Are you okay?

15:44.653 --> 15:47.614
[Ben barking]
[grunts]

15:47.614 --> 15:50.617
- I thought you said
it was plantar fasciitis.

15:50.617 --> 15:51.869
♪ suspenseful music swells ♪

15:53.620 --> 15:56.999
[soft chatter]
[church bell tolling]

15:56.999 --> 15:59.626
- Maxine! [laughs]
- Oh!

15:59.626 --> 16:02.921
- Funny running into you here
in the narthex on my way to the nave.

16:04.006 --> 16:06.884
Did your editor send his theater critic
to review a funeral?

16:06.884 --> 16:07.926
[laughs]

16:08.385 --> 16:11.138
Hey, d-did you happen to see
Donna and Cliff up there?

16:11.138 --> 16:12.389
- I did, in fact.

16:12.389 --> 16:13.849
- And how do they seem?
- Hm?

16:13.849 --> 16:16.393
- You know, I mean, grieving, or more...

16:17.644 --> 16:19.938
upbeat and open-minded?
[sighs]

16:19.938 --> 16:21.356
- I'd say grieving.

16:21.356 --> 16:23.901
- Hey, d-do you know what
might cheer them up?

16:23.901 --> 16:25.694
If you shared your review
of Death Rattle with them.

16:25.694 --> 16:27.196
[chuckles]

16:28.071 --> 16:29.156
- You're not serious.

16:29.156 --> 16:31.533
- [stammering] M-Maybe just give them
a taste, you know?

16:31.533 --> 16:34.077
I mean, "S-sure,
your lead died on opening night,

16:34.077 --> 16:36.663
"but, lucky for you, we don't review
opening night in this business.

16:36.663 --> 16:39.249
"We review press previews
that happened days before.

16:39.249 --> 16:41.668
And the one I saw was a tour de force."

16:41.668 --> 16:43.128
You know, something like that.

16:43.128 --> 16:45.339
Maybe... exactly like that.

16:46.215 --> 16:47.466
- Take care, Oliver.

16:47.466 --> 16:49.468
- Please. Please. Please! Ple--

16:50.135 --> 16:51.637
Please, Maxine.

16:53.305 --> 16:56.016
They're taking down my sets, okay?

16:56.934 --> 16:59.561
After Splash,
I spent 15 years in Broadway jail

16:59.561 --> 17:02.564
thinking about what I'd do if I ever
got another shot, and now this.

17:03.941 --> 17:05.359
Just my luck.

17:06.527 --> 17:07.778
- Come sit.

17:10.864 --> 17:12.658
I am sorry, Oliver,

17:12.658 --> 17:15.869
but I don't think my review
will change anything.

17:15.869 --> 17:17.371
- But I know you liked it.

17:18.372 --> 17:20.916
You have a tell. Do you know that?

17:20.916 --> 17:23.627
You close your notebook
when you love a show you're watching.

17:23.627 --> 17:25.170
I had a spy at the previews.

17:25.170 --> 17:27.881
He said you closed it
halfway through act one.

17:27.881 --> 17:29.716
Are you telling me I'm wrong?

17:29.716 --> 17:31.593
- My pen ran out of ink.

17:31.593 --> 17:33.804
That's why I stopped taking notes.

17:34.388 --> 17:35.639
- Oh.

17:36.139 --> 17:37.391
Well, what does that mean?

17:37.391 --> 17:39.434
- My review was going to be a pan.

17:40.435 --> 17:41.687
- Was it?

17:44.898 --> 17:47.401
Well, what about the performances?
[sad chuckle]

17:48.735 --> 17:50.946
- Oh, I hate to say it, especially here,

17:50.946 --> 17:53.407
but I'm afraid your leading man is giving

17:53.407 --> 17:56.660
a better performance today
than he did the night that I saw him.

17:57.619 --> 18:00.497
- [shocked exhale] Okay...

18:02.082 --> 18:03.876
[sniffs] What about the staging?

18:03.876 --> 18:06.086
- Bland. Bleak.

18:06.086 --> 18:09.089
- You know, Jesus, Maxine!
What are you talking about?

18:09.506 --> 18:12.092
Death Rattle is, is a classic
haunting murder mystery.

18:12.092 --> 18:14.720
It's not supposed to be fun.
- I haven't always been a fan of yours,

18:14.720 --> 18:18.557
but even your worst productions sing!
Somehow.

18:18.557 --> 18:21.852
This one... just didn't sing.

18:21.852 --> 18:23.937
- I mean, I was trying something new.
I was trying--

18:23.937 --> 18:26.982
- Well, it felt stodgy.
And a little scared.

18:27.733 --> 18:29.109
Yes.

18:29.109 --> 18:31.403
[sighs] But don't worry.

18:31.403 --> 18:35.032
Nobody saw my review,
and nobody ever will.

18:35.032 --> 18:38.243
Which... is a shame.

18:38.243 --> 18:41.496
It was some of
my most vitriolic writing. [chuckles]

18:41.496 --> 18:43.332
Peak Maxine.

18:43.332 --> 18:45.417
I never hold back, Oliver.

18:45.417 --> 18:47.211
And neither should you.

18:49.379 --> 18:52.382
♪ melancholy music playing ♪

18:52.382 --> 18:54.760
OLIVER: Come on, Ben.
I can feel you holding back.

18:54.760 --> 18:57.596
J-Just go for it.
- Sorry, but this... [sighs]

18:57.596 --> 18:59.848
This whole falling, heartbeat, heartbeat,

18:59.848 --> 19:01.934
it just sounds weird, right?

19:01.934 --> 19:03.644
Could we lose it?
OLIVER: Well, no.

19:03.644 --> 19:06.021
Just say it how you would say it.

19:06.021 --> 19:07.022
[sighs]

19:08.065 --> 19:09.358
[exhales]

19:09.358 --> 19:12.319
- [affected voice] When you're falling--
When you're fall--

19:12.319 --> 19:14.738
[raspy]
When you're falling, all you can--

19:14.738 --> 19:16.573
[less raspy] When you're falling--
- What's the matter?

19:16.573 --> 19:18.283
- I mean, d-- Come on, don't you hear it?

19:18.283 --> 19:20.953
I s-sound so fucking phony!

19:20.953 --> 19:23.330
- Oh, phony, d-don't say that.
Don't say phony.

19:23.330 --> 19:24.790
- I hate my voice.

19:24.790 --> 19:27.459
OLIVER: Well, I hate to shock you,
all you have is your voice.

19:28.502 --> 19:30.295
You're only a phony if you don't use it.

19:30.295 --> 19:31.588
What's scaring you?

19:31.588 --> 19:34.591
♪ dramatic music playing ♪

19:35.133 --> 19:38.136
- I was Girl Cop. I was CoBro.

19:40.055 --> 19:42.224
What if I can't just be me?

19:42.224 --> 19:44.810
What if I need a ridiculous premise
just to be any good?

19:44.810 --> 19:46.395
- Well, you are doing a play

19:46.395 --> 19:48.689
where a baby is suspected of murder.

19:50.691 --> 19:53.360
Look, Benjamin. Benjamin.

19:54.486 --> 19:57.281
I want you to know it is okay

19:57.865 --> 19:59.366
to just be you.

19:59.366 --> 20:00.993
Look, I'm scared, too.

20:00.993 --> 20:02.244
[gasps]

20:03.287 --> 20:05.831
Scared, but exhilarated.

20:06.248 --> 20:08.125
We're onto something here, Ben.

20:08.667 --> 20:10.210
Come on! Take it again.

20:11.879 --> 20:12.546
[winces]

20:13.630 --> 20:15.591
- [natural voice]
When you're falling...

20:17.259 --> 20:18.844
all you can hear is your heartbeat.

20:18.844 --> 20:21.763
It's been beating since the moment
you were born,

20:21.763 --> 20:24.975
and you never paid it any mind.
Now...

20:24.975 --> 20:27.436
♪ music builds ♪

20:27.436 --> 20:31.231
the last thought that pops in your head,

20:31.231 --> 20:32.774
right before you hit the ground...

20:32.774 --> 20:34.776
[gasping]

20:35.819 --> 20:38.572
"I should have listened to it
while I still had the chance."

20:39.740 --> 20:42.743
[gasping, whimpering]

20:42.743 --> 20:44.786
♪ music crescendos ♪

20:47.206 --> 20:48.540
[straining]
[chain clanging]

20:48.540 --> 20:51.627
- Motherfucker! Motherfucker!

20:51.627 --> 20:54.338
- Hey, you're not gonna rip
this pillar out of the ground.

20:54.338 --> 20:58.091
This is a pre-war building.
If fascism couldn't tear it down...

20:58.091 --> 21:00.344
- Must... get... free!

21:00.344 --> 21:02.095
[restraints clanging]
[sighs]

21:02.095 --> 21:04.097
Fuck! [sighs]

21:05.849 --> 21:07.851
[sighs] What do you think is gonna happen?

21:07.851 --> 21:09.520
- Well,

21:09.520 --> 21:11.480
he killed Ben,

21:11.480 --> 21:14.149
and we know too much, so...

21:17.027 --> 21:19.655
Hey, at least we found the killer.

21:19.655 --> 21:21.532
And in record time.

21:21.532 --> 21:24.117
Usually, it takes us
at least eight episodes.

21:24.701 --> 21:26.703
- Yeah, I guess we did get better.

21:27.871 --> 21:31.416
We managed to solve it
without falsely accusing anyone.

21:31.416 --> 21:34.503
- Or recording people
without their consent.

21:34.503 --> 21:36.505
- Or interrogating a bird.

21:38.257 --> 21:41.009
I'm so sorry I brought us here.

21:41.009 --> 21:44.471
If you die, and it's my fault, I--

21:44.471 --> 21:46.765
- This is not your fault.

21:46.765 --> 21:48.559
I don't blame you
for trying to solve a murder.

21:48.559 --> 21:51.478
You have a strong sense of justice.

21:51.478 --> 21:52.980
And a huge crush on Ben.

21:52.980 --> 21:54.523
- It's not that!

21:55.858 --> 21:57.359
It's not just that.

21:59.653 --> 22:01.113
After my dad died,

22:01.113 --> 22:04.116
my mom wouldn't leave
her bedroom for six months.

22:04.741 --> 22:07.452
I ate a lot of scrambled eggs that year.

22:08.412 --> 22:10.622
I also watched a lot of Girl Cop.

22:11.540 --> 22:13.750
Ben's character on the show was...

22:14.334 --> 22:16.295
sweet and...

22:16.295 --> 22:19.047
I used to dream that
he'd pull up in his dad's Saab

22:19.047 --> 22:21.133
and take me away from that place.

22:21.592 --> 22:23.802
- In a Saab?
- What, it was a cool car.

22:23.802 --> 22:25.804
It looked like a Porsche.

22:25.804 --> 22:26.972
♪

22:26.972 --> 22:29.766
He got me through that time. Us...

22:29.766 --> 22:30.809
through that.

22:31.476 --> 22:33.312
One day, I was watching Girl Cop

22:33.312 --> 22:35.522
and my mom was laughing in her room,

22:35.522 --> 22:37.524
and I thought that was weird.

22:38.775 --> 22:41.069
Then, a few minutes later,

22:41.069 --> 22:44.573
there's a joke on the show,
and we both laughed.

22:45.741 --> 22:49.119
And I realized that we were
watching the same thing.

22:49.119 --> 22:51.622
For 30 minutes a week,

22:51.622 --> 22:54.124
I was laughing with my mom again.

22:55.209 --> 22:57.211
Even if we were in different rooms.

22:59.713 --> 23:01.632
I know he was a dick to you, Charles,

23:01.632 --> 23:03.884
and I didn't really know him...

23:03.884 --> 23:06.261
♪

23:06.261 --> 23:08.472
but, in a weird way,

23:08.472 --> 23:10.140
he meant a lot to me.

23:11.266 --> 23:13.268
- Ben wasn't the dick.

23:13.268 --> 23:14.770
I was.

23:16.605 --> 23:17.856
- What?

23:17.856 --> 23:20.359
- Because if I'd listened
to that heartbeat...

23:21.985 --> 23:24.571
[sighs] maybe none
of this would've happened.

23:25.614 --> 23:27.824
[Oliver clapping]
- That was it. Did you feel it?

23:28.408 --> 23:30.202
Did you feel it, Ben? Okay,

23:30.202 --> 23:32.204
let that sink in.

23:32.788 --> 23:34.540
[sighs] Bravo.

23:39.962 --> 23:41.463
- Hey.

23:42.339 --> 23:43.632
That was great.

23:44.758 --> 23:47.094
- [mocking]
"That was great."

23:47.094 --> 23:48.720
[scoffs]
- What is your problem?

23:48.720 --> 23:51.223
You've been nothing but rude
to me since the table read.

23:52.307 --> 23:55.310
- You seriously don't remember?
- Remember what?

23:58.564 --> 23:59.565
- Brazzos?

23:59.565 --> 24:01.859
- I mean, I remember Brazzos.

24:03.151 --> 24:05.070
[sighs]
What? What?

24:05.070 --> 24:07.281
What, what, what? Were you a fan?

24:07.906 --> 24:09.908
- No, I was an actor!

24:10.534 --> 24:14.162
I-I was cast as a series regular.
Boy genius Timothy Bush?

24:15.998 --> 24:17.124
- Doesn't ring a bell.

24:17.875 --> 24:20.377
- I'd just done
my very first table read ever.

24:20.377 --> 24:21.837
You went over to the director,

24:21.837 --> 24:24.840
told him I was a phony, and got me fired.

24:25.757 --> 24:27.593
I was 8 years old.

24:28.177 --> 24:30.971
- Did you act a lot with your hands?

24:30.971 --> 24:33.223
- Do you have any idea
what that did to me?

24:33.223 --> 24:34.683
It means that every job I go to,

24:34.683 --> 24:37.686
I'm still that little boy
who can't hack it. Even now.

24:38.187 --> 24:39.980
And that insecurity?
I can't walk into a room

24:39.980 --> 24:41.982
without acting like a total jackass.

24:41.982 --> 24:43.400
- Oh, and that's my fault?

24:43.400 --> 24:46.069
- I was a kid!
I was supporting my mom and my brother,

24:46.069 --> 24:47.487
and you fired me.

24:47.487 --> 24:50.032
You know,
I could get you fired off this play.

24:50.824 --> 24:53.827
I could bring things full circle,
but I won't.

24:54.703 --> 24:56.705
I'd rather make it hell for you.

24:57.289 --> 25:00.626
♪

25:06.465 --> 25:08.175
This is my-- You get out.
- Okay, okay, okay!

25:08.175 --> 25:10.969
So, when he showed up to do the play,

25:10.969 --> 25:12.971
I could have made things right,

25:13.680 --> 25:15.682
but I didn't.

25:15.682 --> 25:17.643
And now, it's too late.

25:17.643 --> 25:19.061
[door slams]

25:21.772 --> 25:24.650
[cart creaking]

25:24.650 --> 25:26.985
GREGG: Alrighty, now!
[rattling]

25:27.653 --> 25:30.906
- You can kill me any way you want,
but make hers quick and painless.

25:30.906 --> 25:32.241
[clanging]

25:32.241 --> 25:34.785
Actually,
we'll take two quick and painless.

25:34.785 --> 25:37.079
[rummaging]
- What the fuck is that?

25:37.079 --> 25:38.747
- It's a kitchen torch.

25:38.747 --> 25:40.541
I stole it from the pastry chef at work.

25:40.541 --> 25:42.501
- I thought you said
you were a security guard.

25:42.501 --> 25:45.629
- I lied. I work at Lulu's Steakhouse
on 51st and 7th.

25:45.629 --> 25:49.132
Chef Bobby doesn't think
I'm "sous-chef" material.

25:49.132 --> 25:51.510
Punk-ass bitch.
He should see me now.

25:51.510 --> 25:52.511
[click]

25:53.512 --> 25:54.513
[click]

25:54.805 --> 25:55.806
Come on.

25:55.806 --> 25:57.724
- They usually have a safety.
- Charles!

25:57.724 --> 26:00.227
- Huh. Thanks, Charles.
That's cool of you. You're right.

26:00.853 --> 26:02.688
- Gregg,
you're not gonna get away with this!

26:02.688 --> 26:03.730
- No, you aren't!

26:03.730 --> 26:05.816
♪

26:05.816 --> 26:08.402
I saw how you squirmed at the service.

26:08.402 --> 26:10.571
How uncomfortable you were.

26:10.571 --> 26:12.072
You hated Ben!

26:12.990 --> 26:14.616
So much so that you killed him!

26:14.616 --> 26:15.617
- No!
- Wait, what?

26:15.617 --> 26:17.703
Charles didn't kill him. You did.

26:17.703 --> 26:21.081
- Me? No, I loved him,
and you took him from me! Confess!

26:21.081 --> 26:22.916
Confess!
- Help! Help!

26:22.916 --> 26:25.752
[muffled yelling]

26:25.752 --> 26:28.005
- What?
- Where'd you get that hankie?

26:30.966 --> 26:33.093
- I stole it from Ben's the night he died

26:33.093 --> 26:34.970
when I was looking for clues
and collectibles.

26:34.970 --> 26:37.890
- Wait, you broke into-- [muffled yelling]

26:37.890 --> 26:39.641
- Admit it! You killed him!

26:39.641 --> 26:41.977
- Kill!? I wouldn't kill-- [blowing]
- Say it!

26:41.977 --> 26:43.103
[door slams]
Say it--

26:43.103 --> 26:44.980
OFFICER 1: Hands up!
OFFICER 2: Drop the blowtorch!

26:44.980 --> 26:46.690
Let me see your hands!
- I didn't do anything.

26:46.690 --> 26:48.692
OFFICER 2:
Take him! Gimme your hands.

26:48.692 --> 26:51.028
[panting]
[police radio chatter]

26:51.028 --> 26:52.613
Got him?

26:52.613 --> 26:54.823
Check his pockets.
GREGG: I didn't do anything!

26:54.823 --> 26:57.034
[handcuffs clicking]
- I'm Detective Biswas.

26:57.034 --> 26:59.286
[Gregg groans]
You must be the podcasters.

26:59.286 --> 27:00.621
Williams told me about you guys.

27:00.621 --> 27:02.706
- Detective Williams
told you we were down here?

27:02.706 --> 27:05.125
- No, she told me
you're a pain in the ass.

27:05.542 --> 27:08.128
We've been on this guy
for the past 48 hours.

27:08.128 --> 27:09.755
Someone saw him book it out of the Arconia

27:09.755 --> 27:11.798
two minutes after Ben Glenroy died.

27:11.798 --> 27:14.426
You know he's a stalker, right?

27:15.260 --> 27:17.721
What the fuck were you thinking?

27:17.721 --> 27:18.722
[Mabel grunts]

27:19.306 --> 27:20.516
- Thank you.
BISWAS: Wait.

27:24.102 --> 27:25.562
Aren't there's supposed
to be three of you?

27:26.939 --> 27:29.691
- We have his address, if you need it.

27:30.359 --> 27:32.152
[sighs]
[Velcro ripping]

27:32.819 --> 27:33.820
[sighs]

27:35.697 --> 27:37.866
- [sighs] You've had a minor heart attack.

27:37.866 --> 27:39.576
- Oh, my God, Dad.

27:39.576 --> 27:42.079
- He said minor, Willie. I mean...

27:43.330 --> 27:45.999
Plus, that's just a rite of passage
in the theater, you know.

27:45.999 --> 27:48.252
Bob Fosse had, like, five.

27:48.252 --> 27:49.503
- Yeah, you know the last one
killed him, right?

27:49.503 --> 27:51.588
- Aw, you did read his biography.

27:51.588 --> 27:53.173
[sighs]

27:53.173 --> 27:56.468
- Uh, there are a few things
we need to talk about.

27:57.135 --> 27:59.221
First is your blood pressure.

27:59.221 --> 28:00.597
It's 160 over 100.

28:00.597 --> 28:02.015
- And is that high?

28:02.015 --> 28:02.933
- Yes.
- Yes.

28:04.476 --> 28:05.519
- And is high good?

28:05.519 --> 28:06.770
- No!
DOCTOR: No.

28:07.896 --> 28:10.315
- Uh, I'm going to prescribe
you some medications,

28:10.315 --> 28:13.861
but you need to change your diet, too.
Cut out dips.

28:13.861 --> 28:15.571
- Doctor, are you trying to kill me?

28:16.613 --> 28:18.240
- You also have an arrhythmia,

28:18.240 --> 28:20.450
so I'm giving you this Holter monitor.

28:20.450 --> 28:23.704
It sits right here across your chest.

28:23.704 --> 28:25.706
And when you feel an irregular heartbeat,

28:25.706 --> 28:27.749
you press the button, like that.
[beeps]

28:27.749 --> 28:29.585
That way, we can keep track of them.

28:29.585 --> 28:32.254
- B-But I'm healthy enough
to still direct a play, right?

28:32.254 --> 28:33.630
DOCTOR:
Only if you think it's healthy

28:33.630 --> 28:36.175
to pretend you didn't
just have a heart attack.

28:36.175 --> 28:38.969
You need to reduce stress.

28:38.969 --> 28:41.180
Hm? Because if there's a next time,

28:41.180 --> 28:42.890
it might not be so small.

28:46.768 --> 28:48.604
- PTSD check.

28:48.604 --> 28:50.814
How are we holding up?
- Okay.

28:50.814 --> 28:52.608
I've already repressed it.

28:52.608 --> 28:53.984
- That's good.

28:54.526 --> 28:56.028
So...

28:56.945 --> 28:59.072
I think the police have the wrong guy.

28:59.489 --> 29:01.283
- Mabel--
- Please, just hear me out!

29:01.283 --> 29:03.952
Gregg didn't hate Ben.
He loved him.

29:03.952 --> 29:07.039
- You're splitting psychopathic hairs!
He kidnapped us!

29:07.039 --> 29:10.000
- But only because he wanted
to find the killer.

29:10.000 --> 29:13.003
I mean, he wanted to find
the killer so badly

29:13.003 --> 29:15.130
that he was willing to
commit multiple felonies.

29:15.130 --> 29:16.423
[presses button]

29:16.423 --> 29:19.426
Come on, you know I'm right.
Plus, there's this.

29:21.136 --> 29:22.763
If Gregg had Ben's handkerchief,

29:22.763 --> 29:26.141
then whose handkerchief
was Ben holding when he died?

29:26.141 --> 29:29.144
♪

29:30.145 --> 29:31.396
- Where'd you get these?

29:32.731 --> 29:34.942
- Well, I...
[shutter snapping]

29:34.942 --> 29:38.153
CHARLES: You tampered with a crime scene
and took photos?!

29:38.153 --> 29:40.155
I find this highly concerning.

29:41.448 --> 29:44.159
And, at the same time,
I am very impressed.

29:44.159 --> 29:46.411
[bell dings, doors open]

29:47.246 --> 29:51.166
So, why was Ben holding that handkerchief?

29:51.166 --> 29:53.085
- So what if...
[heartbeat thumping]

29:53.085 --> 29:55.879
What if Ben, before he fell...

29:57.214 --> 29:59.508
what if he tried to grab onto something?

29:59.508 --> 30:01.718
CHARLES:
Right, and all he could reach

30:01.718 --> 30:03.762
was the killer's pocket square.

30:05.055 --> 30:06.807
MABEL:
Or...

30:06.807 --> 30:09.560
the killer had it in their hair
or around their neck.

30:10.727 --> 30:12.187
CHARLES:
Or, I don't know,

30:12.187 --> 30:15.148
maybe he ripped it
right out of the killer's hand.

30:15.148 --> 30:17.067
MABEL: Okay, so,

30:17.067 --> 30:18.694
are you in?

30:19.528 --> 30:20.571
- Yeah.

30:24.700 --> 30:25.826
[blows]

30:26.535 --> 30:27.536
Yeah...

30:27.536 --> 30:28.787
- Oh, we'll get there.

30:29.788 --> 30:32.791
[heartbeat thumping]

30:32.791 --> 30:35.419
DOCTOR [echoing]:
You need to reduce stress.

30:35.419 --> 30:38.297
[sighs]
MAXINE [echoing]: Bland. Bleak.

30:39.464 --> 30:42.843
[quiet snapping]
This one... just didn't sing.

30:42.843 --> 30:44.845
Just didn't sing.

30:45.846 --> 30:47.890
I never hold back, Oliver.
[stage lights click]

30:47.890 --> 30:49.516
And neither should you.
[lights sparkling]

30:49.516 --> 30:51.226
[jazzy heartbeat]

30:51.226 --> 30:52.644
[drum roll]
[Oliver snorts]

30:52.644 --> 30:56.023
- Ladies and gentlemen,
let's take it from the top.

30:56.023 --> 30:59.276
♪ Fosse-style jazz music playing ♪

30:59.276 --> 31:01.278
[snapping continues]

31:01.278 --> 31:04.031
♪ music crescendos ♪

31:04.031 --> 31:06.867
♪

31:07.910 --> 31:11.496
- Relax, Putnam.
You know I'm not into this musical shit.

31:11.496 --> 31:13.373
♪ dramatic sting ♪

31:14.374 --> 31:15.834
♪

31:15.834 --> 31:18.086
You're making a mess of things, Oliver.

31:18.086 --> 31:20.339
- She's right. You better listen.

31:20.339 --> 31:21.757
- Listen, up, Daddy.

31:21.757 --> 31:23.008
- ♪ You've got too much stress ♪

31:23.008 --> 31:24.885
- ♪ Uh-huh ♪
- ♪ Let it go ♪

31:24.885 --> 31:25.802
- ♪ Yeah ♪

31:25.802 --> 31:27.179
- ♪ You're a mess ♪

31:27.763 --> 31:29.431
♪ Too much stress ♪
- ♪ Ah ♪

31:29.431 --> 31:30.641
- ♪ The show, the show, the show ♪

31:30.641 --> 31:32.518
♪ The show, the show can't go on ♪

31:33.560 --> 31:36.146
♪ Stop, stop, stop ♪

31:36.146 --> 31:37.731
♪ Please stop ♪

31:37.731 --> 31:38.649
♪ finale sting ♪

31:39.525 --> 31:42.361
[ding, ringing]

31:42.361 --> 31:45.364
♪ whimsical music playing ♪

31:47.074 --> 31:49.785
- Donna, Cliff, trust me.
You'll love it!

31:50.661 --> 31:52.037
You'll hear me out?

31:53.539 --> 31:56.625
I love you both. Give each other
a big kiss on the lips for me.

31:56.625 --> 31:59.628
Big news, people!
First of all, Charles,

31:59.628 --> 32:02.256
you should consider sequins,
and a lot of them.

32:02.256 --> 32:03.882
- Uh, no thanks, and let's move on.

32:03.882 --> 32:05.133
- Second, I'm listening to my heart

32:05.133 --> 32:07.135
and re-imagining Death Rattle

32:07.135 --> 32:09.263
in the most Oliver Putnam way.

32:09.263 --> 32:10.472
[panting]

32:10.472 --> 32:13.308
I'm gonna make it sing, goddamn it!

32:13.308 --> 32:14.810
That's right, folks.

32:15.602 --> 32:17.479
It's a musical. [snorts]

32:17.479 --> 32:20.357
Get ready for Death Rattle dazzle!

32:21.358 --> 32:22.860
What are you doing with that?

32:23.735 --> 32:25.362
- The cops got it wrong.

32:25.362 --> 32:28.615
We think that Ben's killer
is someone in your show.

32:28.615 --> 32:30.742
- Which means...
[beep]

32:30.742 --> 32:32.244
- We're back.

32:32.244 --> 32:35.122
[panting]

32:35.122 --> 32:38.166
[monitor beeps]
[snorts, whimpers]

32:39.877 --> 32:42.880
♪
